"analysis": "The Executor loaded the telemetry files and returned compact summaries. Metric and trace data are available and cover timestamps from 1614859200 up to ~1614861000 (which includes the target incident window). The log.csv and error_logs.csv are empty, so log-based localization will be limited. From the metric summary we see many component-KPI series (e.g., apache01, apache02, IG01, Redis01) with ~31 points each; trace summary shows many trace series for IG01, Tomcat02/03, MG02 with ~30–31 points. No thresholds or anomaly detection have been done yet. Given logs are empty, metrics and traces will be primary sources for localization.",
"completed": "False",
"instruction": "Using metric.csv only, compute global thresholds for every component-KPI time series (use the full available series in the file). For each distinct (cmdb_id, kpi_name) produce: count, min_timestamp, max_timestamp, mean, median, P95 (95th percentile), and P5 (5th percentile). Also output the distinct list of cmdb_id values present in metric.csv that match the allowed root-cause component list [apache01, apache02, Tomcat01, Tomcat02, Tomcat03, Tomcat04, MG01, MG02, IG01, IG02, Mysql01, Mysql02, Redis01, Redis02]. Return at most the top 20 component-KPI rows sorted by count (desc). Do not filter by the incident time window yet and do not perform anomaly detection. Return the compact table only."
}

{
"analysis": "We have computed global statistics (mean, median, P95, P5) for each component-KPI using the full metric series. The metric and trace data cover the incident period (timestamps around 1614859200–1614861000). log.csv and error_logs.csv are empty, so we must rely on metrics and traces. Next we should detect anomalies inside the incident window (March 4, 2021 20:00–20:30) by comparing metric points in that window against the previously computed global thresholds (P95 and P5). Anomalies are defined as points >= P95 or <= P5. From those anomalies we can shortlist candidate faulty component-KPIs and their earliest anomaly timestamps for further fault identification and trace analysis.",
"completed": "False",
"instruction": "Using the previously computed global thresholds for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name), filter metric.csv to the incident window March 4, 2021 20:00 to 20:30 (inclusive). For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) identify points in that window where value >= P95 OR value <= P5 (use the P95 and P5 values computed from the full series). Produce a compact table (limit to top 20 rows sorted by anomaly count desc) with these columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, and up to 3 sample anomaly rows (timestamp:value). If no anomalies are found for any series, return an explicit empty result. Do not compute new global thresholds; use existing P95/P5 from the full series."
}

{
"analysis": "The last Executor run attempted to detect anomalies in the incident window using the previously computed global P95/P5 thresholds, but the execution returned None (no visible result). From prior steps we know metric.csv contains series with min_timestamp ~1614859200 and max_timestamp ~1614861000 which should overlap the incident window (March 4, 2021 20:00–20:30 UTC+8). However the recent run did not provide a concrete anomaly summary, so it is unclear whether (a) the incident window selection yielded zero metric points, (b) the anomaly test found zero anomalies, or (c) the result simply wasn't returned/printed. We must resolve this ambiguity by asking the Executor to explicitly report counts and a concise anomaly sample. Logs and error_logs are empty so metrics and traces remain primary sources.",
"completed": "False",
"instruction": "Re-run a compact, explicit check for the incident window: \n1) Compute and return three scalar counts: total number of metric rows in the incident window (2021-03-04 20:00 to 20:30 UTC+8 inclusive), total number of anomaly points in that window using the previously computed per-(cmdb_id,kpi_name) P95/P5 thresholds (anomaly if value >= P95 or value <= P5), and the number of distinct (cmdb_id,kpi_name) series that contain at least one anomaly in the window.\n2) If anomaly_count > 0, return up to 20 anomaly rows (limit=20) with columns: timestamp, cmdb_id, kpi_name, value, p95, p5, is_anomaly, sorted by timestamp asc. If anomaly_count == 0, return an explicit message saying no anomalies were found in the window.\n\nNotes: use the existing precomputed P95/P5 per series (do not recompute thresholds using only the window). Do not convert timestamps to datetimes in the output. Keep the output compact and explicit."
}

{
"analysis": "The last Executor run attempted to report metric-window anomaly counts using the previously computed global P95/P5 thresholds but returned no visible output (None). From earlier successful steps we know metric.csv and trace.csv cover the incident timeframe and log.csv / error_logs.csv are empty, so logs won't help. Because the metric-window anomaly check produced no explicit result, we cannot yet conclude whether there truly are zero metric anomalies in the incident window or whether the previous run simply didn't print the output. To progress, we should analyze traces next (following threshold calculation -> data extraction -> metric analysis -> trace analysis order). Trace analysis requires computing global thresholds per (cmdb_id, trace_name) across the full trace series before filtering to the incident window, then detecting anomalies in the window. If trace anomalies are found, they can guide root-cause localization when metrics are silent.",
"completed": "False",
"instruction": "For trace.csv only: 1) Compute global P95 and P5 for each distinct (cmdb_id, trace_name) using the full trace.csv series. 2) Filter trace.csv to the incident window March 4, 2021 20:00 to 20:30 UTC+8 (inclusive). 3) Using the per-(cmdb_id,trace_name) global P95/P5, mark trace rows in the window as anomalies if value >= P95 or value <= P5. 4) Return a compact result with three scalar counts: total trace rows in window, total anomaly points in window, number of distinct (cmdb_id, trace_name) series with ≥1 anomaly. 5) If anomaly_count > 0, also return up to 20 anomaly rows with columns: timestamp, cmdb_id, trace_name, value, p95, p5, is_anomaly, sorted by timestamp ascending. If anomaly_count == 0, return an explicit message saying no trace anomalies were found. Do not convert timestamps to datetimes and do not recompute thresholds using only the window."
}

{
"analysis": "Metric anomaly detection using global P95/P5 thresholds (computed from full series) within the incident window found widespread anomalies across allowed components: 27,080 metric rows considered for allowed components, 18,338 anomaly points, and 1,621 distinct (cmdb_id,kpi_name) series with ≥1 anomaly. Many series show all 31 points flagged (anomaly_count=31) starting at earliest timestamp 1614859200; examples include JVM heap maxima and zero-valued TCP counters. This indicates broad extreme values in the window rather than isolated spikes. To move from many anomalous KPIs to candidate root-cause components, we need component-level severity and early-occurrence information, and to know whether anomalies are mostly upper-bound breaches (>=P95) or lower-bound breaches (<=P5). That will let us pick components for targeted trace analysis (to find the most downstream faulty service). Trace and log data will be used next for localization, but first we must rank components by anomaly severity and timing.",
"completed": "False",
"instruction": "Aggregate the metric anomaly results at component level (use the previously merged windowed metric data that includes p95 and p5 and is_anomaly flags). For each cmdb_id in the allowed root-cause list produce a compact row with these fields: cmdb_id, total_anomaly_points (count of rows where is_anomaly==True), distinct_anomalous_kpis (count of distinct kpi_name with ≥1 anomaly), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (min timestamp among anomaly rows), count_above_p95 (number of anomaly rows where value >= p95), count_below_p5 (number of anomaly rows where value <= p5), and max_relative_deviation (for each anomaly row compute relative deviation = abs(value - threshold)/threshold where threshold is p95 for above-threshold anomalies or p5 for below-threshold anomalies; report the maximum relative deviation observed per component, rounded reasonably). Also include top_kpis (up to 3 kpi_name values for that component with the largest anomaly counts, formatted as kpi1(count) | kpi2(count) | kpi3(count)). Return at most top 20 components sorted by total_anomaly_points descending. Keep output compact and textual (one line per component). If no anomaly rows exist in memory, return an explicit message saying no anomalies to aggregate." }

